[2026-03-10T16:32:15Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016jUx5DTeN7VJfgbeyCLgR1","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile a comprehensive report:\n\n## Exploration Complete\n\nI've conducted a thorough exploration of the Cloche codebase. Here's a comprehensive report on the structure, how it works, and where to add delete/cleanup functionality on the Project details page.\n\n### 1. Web UI Structure\n\n**Files:**\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` - Main HTTP handler with routing and business logic\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/layout.html` - Base template\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/project_detail.html` - Project details page\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/run_detail.html` - Run detail page\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/runs.html` - Runs list\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html` - Projects overview\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/static/style.css` - Button and UI styling\n\n**Routes Defined** (lines 122-138 in handler.go):\n- `GET /` - Project overview\n- `GET /projects/{name}` - Project details page → calls `handleProjectDetail()`\n- `GET /projects/{name}/info` - API endpoint for project info\n- `GET /projects/{name}/workflows` - API endpoint for workflows\n- `GET /projects/{name}/runs` - Redirect to `/runs?project=<dir>`\n- `DELETE /api/runs/{id}/container` - **Existing container delete endpoint** → calls `handleAPIDeleteContainer()`\n\n### 2. Project Details Page Structure\n\n**Template:** `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/project_detail.html`\n- Displays project info (Docker image, version, prompt files)\n- Shows recent runs with history dots\n- Displays workflows as a DAG\n- All dynamic content loaded via JavaScript fetch calls to `/api/projects/{name}/info` and `/api/projects/{name}/workflows`\n\n**Key Data Passed to Template:**\n```go\nmap[string]any{\n    \"Title\":      label,\n    \"Label\":      label,\n    \"Dir\":        dir,\n    \"RecentRuns\": dots,\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Container Management Architecture\n\n**Key Types:**\n\n**Domain Model** (`/workspace/internal/domain/run.go`):\n```go\ntype Run struct {\n    ID             string\n    ContainerID    string           // Docker container ID\n    ContainerKept  bool             // true when container retained after run completion\n    // ... other fields\n}\n```\n\n**Container Interface** (`/workspace/internal/ports/container.go`):\n```go\ntype ContainerRuntime interface {\n    Start(ctx context.Context, cfg ContainerConfig) (containerID string, err error)\n    Stop(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error\n    Remove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error  // <- Delete operation\n    Logs(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (string, error)\n    Inspect(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (*ContainerStatus, error)\n    // ... other methods\n}\n```\n\n**Docker Implementation** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`):\n```go\nfunc (r *Runtime) Remove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error {\n    // Executes: docker rm <containerID>\n}\n```\n\n**Persistence** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/sqlite/store.go`):\n- `container_kept` INTEGER column in `runs` table (lines 81)\n- Used to track whether container was retained for inspection/debugging\n\n### 4. Projects ↔ Containers Association\n\n**How Projects Track Containers:**\n1. `Run` has `ProjectDir` field linking it to a project\n2. `Run` has `ContainerID` field linking it to a Docker container\n3. In `handleRunsList()` (handler.go, lines 246-253), containers are counted per project:\n```go\ncontainerCounts := map[string]int{}\nfor _, run := range allRuns {\n    if run.ContainerKept {\n        containerCounts[run.ProjectDir]++\n    }\n}\n```\n\n4. In `/runs` page, container count shown per project: `(N containers)`\n\n### 5. Existing Delete/Cleanup Patterns\n\n**Already Implemented - Container Deletion on Run Detail Page:**\n\n**Web Handler** (handler.go, lines 679-715):\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) handleAPIDeleteContainer(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    // 1. Get run by ID\n    // 2. Get ContainerManager (which has Remove method)\n    // 3. Call mgr.Remove(ctx, containerID)\n    // 4. Update run.ContainerKept = false\n    // 5. Save run to database\n}\n```\n\n**Route:** `DELETE /api/runs/{id}/container`\n\n**HTML Button** (run_detail.html, line 25):\n```html\n<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" id=\"delete-container-btn\" \n        onclick=\"deleteContainer('{{.Run.ID}}')\">\n    Delete Container\n</button>\n```\n\n**JavaScript Handler** (run_detail.html, lines 275-293):\n```javascript\nwindow.deleteContainer = function(runID) {\n    var btn = document.getElementById('delete-container-btn');\n    if (btn) btn.disabled = true;\n    fetch('/api/runs/' + runID + '/container', { method: 'DELETE' })\n        .then(function(r) { return r.json().then(...); })\n        // Updates UI to show \"Container removed\"\n};\n```\n\n**Container State Display** (handler.go, lines 339-363):\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) containerState(ctx context.Context, run *domain.Run) string {\n    // Returns: \"running\", \"stopped\", \"available\", or \"removed\"\n    // \"available\" = kept container that can be deleted\n}\n```\n\n### 6. Button/Action Styling Patterns\n\n**Available Button Classes** (style.css, lines 342-385):\n- `.btn` - Base style\n- `.btn-primary` - Blue button (background: var(--link))\n- `.btn-secondary` - White button with blue text (used for View Runs)\n- `.btn-danger` - Red button (background: var(--badge-failed-bg))\n- `.btn-sm` - Small button size\n- `:disabled` - Opacity 0.6, cursor not-allowed\n\n**Example Button Usage:**\n- Line 27 in projects.html: `<a href=\"/projects/{{.Label}}/runs\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\">View Runs</a>`\n- Line 25 in run_detail.html: `<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" ... >Delete Container</button>`\n- Line 6 in run_detail.html: `<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" ... >Cancel</button>`\n\n### 7. Web Handler Initialization\n\n**File:** `/workspace/cmd/cloched/main.go` (lines 85-95):\n```go\nwebOpts := []web.HandlerOption{\n    web.WithContainerLogger(runtime),     // Docker runtime\n    web.WithLogStore(store),\n    web.WithLogBroadcaster(broadcaster),\n}\nwebHandler, err := web.NewHandler(store, store, webOpts...)\n```\n\n**Handler Setup** (handler.go, lines 54-75):\n- Implements `ContainerLogger` interface (minimal: just Logs method)\n- Can optionally implement `ContainerManager` interface (extends ContainerLogger with Stop/Remove/Inspect)\n- Set via `WithContainerManager()` option (line 37-38)\n\n### 8. Key Wiring Points\n\n**Handler Field Dependencies** (handler.go, lines 68-76):\n```go\ntype Handler struct {\n    store        ports.RunStore\n    captures     ports.CaptureStore\n    logStore     ports.LogStore\n    container    ContainerLogger              // Can be cast to ContainerManager\n    logBroadcast *logstream.Broadcaster\n    pages        map[string]*template.Template\n    mux          *http.ServeMux\n}\n```\n\n**Container Operations Check** (handler.go, lines 348-350):\n```go\nmgr, ok := h.container.(ContainerManager)\nif !ok {\n    return \"removed\"  // Container management not available\n}\n```\n\n### Summary for Implementation\n\nTo add delete buttons on the Project details page, you would:\n\n1. **Add API endpoint** similar to `handleAPIDeleteContainer()` that:\n   - Takes a run ID or list of run IDs\n   - Filters runs by project directory\n   - Deletes their containers via `ContainerManager.Remove()`\n   - Updates `ContainerKept = false` for each run\n\n2. **Add UI elements** to `project_detail.html`:\n   - List retained containers (from recent runs where `ContainerKept = true`)\n   - Add delete buttons with `.btn .btn-danger .btn-sm` styling\n   - Call JavaScript function to POST/DELETE to the new endpoint\n\n3. **Add JavaScript handler** in the project detail template:\n   - Similar to `deleteContainer()` but for bulk operations\n   - Update UI to show success/failure\n   - Refresh container list after deletion\n\nThe architecture is already well-designed with the `ContainerManager` interface providing all needed operations (Stop, Remove, Inspect). The existing implementation on the Run detail page serves as a perfect template."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a5f6caa84391449d3 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 67470\ntool_uses: 27\nduration_ms: 52893</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"88dee606-b80e-44b4-9205-0d160e19ebe3","uuid":"7ef19988-d672-4fa1-b7a8-911e66eec7b3","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Explore the codebase to understand:\n\n1. The web UI structure - find all web handler files, templates, and routes, especially the Project details page\n2. How containers are managed - find the container runtime adapter, especially any existing delete/remove functionality\n3. How projects are associated with containers\n4. The existing patterns for buttons/actions on web pages\n\nSearch thoroughly for:\n- Web handlers (likely in internal/adapters/ somewhere)\n- HTML templates\n- Container-related code (Docker adapter)\n- Project details page specifically\n- Any existing delete/cleanup functionality for containers\n\nReport file paths, key types/interfaces, and how things are wired together.","agentId":"a5f6caa84391449d3","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile a comprehensive report:\n\n## Exploration Complete\n\nI've conducted a thorough exploration of the Cloche codebase. Here's a comprehensive report on the structure, how it works, and where to add delete/cleanup functionality on the Project details page.\n\n### 1. Web UI Structure\n\n**Files:**\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` - Main HTTP handler with routing and business logic\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/layout.html` - Base template\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/project_detail.html` - Project details page\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/run_detail.html` - Run detail page\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/runs.html` - Runs list\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html` - Projects overview\n- `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/static/style.css` - Button and UI styling\n\n**Routes Defined** (lines 122-138 in handler.go):\n- `GET /` - Project overview\n- `GET /projects/{name}` - Project details page → calls `handleProjectDetail()`\n- `GET /projects/{name}/info` - API endpoint for project info\n- `GET /projects/{name}/workflows` - API endpoint for workflows\n- `GET /projects/{name}/runs` - Redirect to `/runs?project=<dir>`\n- `DELETE /api/runs/{id}/container` - **Existing container delete endpoint** → calls `handleAPIDeleteContainer()`\n\n### 2. Project Details Page Structure\n\n**Template:** `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/templates/project_detail.html`\n- Displays project info (Docker image, version, prompt files)\n- Shows recent runs with history dots\n- Displays workflows as a DAG\n- All dynamic content loaded via JavaScript fetch calls to `/api/projects/{name}/info` and `/api/projects/{name}/workflows`\n\n**Key Data Passed to Template:**\n```go\nmap[string]any{\n    \"Title\":      label,\n    \"Label\":      label,\n    \"Dir\":        dir,\n    \"RecentRuns\": dots,\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Container Management Architecture\n\n**Key Types:**\n\n**Domain Model** (`/workspace/internal/domain/run.go`):\n```go\ntype Run struct {\n    ID             string\n    ContainerID    string           // Docker container ID\n    ContainerKept  bool             // true when container retained after run completion\n    // ... other fields\n}\n```\n\n**Container Interface** (`/workspace/internal/ports/container.go`):\n```go\ntype ContainerRuntime interface {\n    Start(ctx context.Context, cfg ContainerConfig) (containerID string, err error)\n    Stop(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error\n    Remove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error  // <- Delete operation\n    Logs(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (string, error)\n    Inspect(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (*ContainerStatus, error)\n    // ... other methods\n}\n```\n\n**Docker Implementation** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`):\n```go\nfunc (r *Runtime) Remove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error {\n    // Executes: docker rm <containerID>\n}\n```\n\n**Persistence** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/sqlite/store.go`):\n- `container_kept` INTEGER column in `runs` table (lines 81)\n- Used to track whether container was retained for inspection/debugging\n\n### 4. Projects ↔ Containers Association\n\n**How Projects Track Containers:**\n1. `Run` has `ProjectDir` field linking it to a project\n2. `Run` has `ContainerID` field linking it to a Docker container\n3. In `handleRunsList()` (handler.go, lines 246-253), containers are counted per project:\n```go\ncontainerCounts := map[string]int{}\nfor _, run := range allRuns {\n    if run.ContainerKept {\n        containerCounts[run.ProjectDir]++\n    }\n}\n```\n\n4. In `/runs` page, container count shown per project: `(N containers)`\n\n### 5. Existing Delete/Cleanup Patterns\n\n**Already Implemented - Container Deletion on Run Detail Page:**\n\n**Web Handler** (handler.go, lines 679-715):\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) handleAPIDeleteContainer(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    // 1. Get run by ID\n    // 2. Get ContainerManager (which has Remove method)\n    // 3. Call mgr.Remove(ctx, containerID)\n    // 4. Update run.ContainerKept = false\n    // 5. Save run to database\n}\n```\n\n**Route:** `DELETE /api/runs/{id}/container`\n\n**HTML Button** (run_detail.html, line 25):\n```html\n<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" id=\"delete-container-btn\" \n        onclick=\"deleteContainer('{{.Run.ID}}')\">\n    Delete Container\n</button>\n```\n\n**JavaScript Handler** (run_detail.html, lines 275-293):\n```javascript\nwindow.deleteContainer = function(runID) {\n    var btn = document.getElementById('delete-container-btn');\n    if (btn) btn.disabled = true;\n    fetch('/api/runs/' + runID + '/container', { method: 'DELETE' })\n        .then(function(r) { return r.json().then(...); })\n        // Updates UI to show \"Container removed\"\n};\n```\n\n**Container State Display** (handler.go, lines 339-363):\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) containerState(ctx context.Context, run *domain.Run) string {\n    // Returns: \"running\", \"stopped\", \"available\", or \"removed\"\n    // \"available\" = kept container that can be deleted\n}\n```\n\n### 6. Button/Action Styling Patterns\n\n**Available Button Classes** (style.css, lines 342-385):\n- `.btn` - Base style\n- `.btn-primary` - Blue button (background: var(--link))\n- `.btn-secondary` - White button with blue text (used for View Runs)\n- `.btn-danger` - Red button (background: var(--badge-failed-bg))\n- `.btn-sm` - Small button size\n- `:disabled` - Opacity 0.6, cursor not-allowed\n\n**Example Button Usage:**\n- Line 27 in projects.html: `<a href=\"/projects/{{.Label}}/runs\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\">View Runs</a>`\n- Line 25 in run_detail.html: `<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" ... >Delete Container</button>`\n- Line 6 in run_detail.html: `<button class=\"btn btn-danger btn-sm\" ... >Cancel</button>`\n\n### 7. Web Handler Initialization\n\n**File:** `/workspace/cmd/cloched/main.go` (lines 85-95):\n```go\nwebOpts := []web.HandlerOption{\n    web.WithContainerLogger(runtime),     // Docker runtime\n    web.WithLogStore(store),\n    web.WithLogBroadcaster(broadcaster),\n}\nwebHandler, err := web.NewHandler(store, store, webOpts...)\n```\n\n**Handler Setup** (handler.go, lines 54-75):\n- Implements `ContainerLogger` interface (minimal: just Logs method)\n- Can optionally implement `ContainerManager` interface (extends ContainerLogger with Stop/Remove/Inspect)\n- Set via `WithContainerManager()` option (line 37-38)\n\n### 8. Key Wiring Points\n\n**Handler Field Dependencies** (handler.go, lines 68-76):\n```go\ntype Handler struct {\n    store        ports.RunStore\n    captures     ports.CaptureStore\n    logStore     ports.LogStore\n    container    ContainerLogger              // Can be cast to ContainerManager\n    logBroadcast *logstream.Broadcaster\n    pages        map[string]*template.Template\n    mux          *http.ServeMux\n}\n```\n\n**Container Operations Check** (handler.go, lines 348-350):\n```go\nmgr, ok := h.container.(ContainerManager)\nif !ok {\n    return \"removed\"  // Container management not available\n}\n```\n\n### Summary for Implementation\n\nTo add delete buttons on the Project details page, you would:\n\n1. **Add API endpoint** similar to `handleAPIDeleteContainer()` that:\n   - Takes a run ID or list of run IDs\n   - Filters runs by project directory\n   - Deletes their containers via `ContainerManager.Remove()`\n   - Updates `ContainerKept = false` for each run\n\n2. **Add UI elements** to `project_detail.html`:\n   - List retained containers (from recent runs where `ContainerKept = true`)\n   - Add delete buttons with `.btn .btn-danger .btn-sm` styling\n   - Call JavaScript function to POST/DELETE to the new endpoint\n\n3. **Add JavaScript handler** in the project detail template:\n   - Similar to `deleteContainer()` but for bulk operations\n   - Update UI to show success/failure\n   - Refresh container list after deletion\n\nThe architecture is already well-designed with the `ContainerManager` interface providing all needed operations (Stop, Remove, Inspect). The existing implementation on the Run detail page serves as a perfect template."}],"totalDurationMs":52893,"totalTokens":67470,"totalToolUseCount":27,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3050,"cache_read_input_token